14.5.15. 

Language is a part of our organism and no less complicated than it. 
[Cf. 4.002.] 

The old problem of complex and fact! 

15.5.15. 

The theory of the complex is expressed in such propositions as: 
"If a proposition is true then Something exists"; there seems to be a 
difference between the fact expressed by the proposition: a stands in 
the relation R to b, and the complex: a in the relation R to b, which is 
just that which "exists" if that proposition is true. It seems as if we 
could designate this Something, and what's more with a real "complex 
sign" — the feelings expressed in these sentences are quite natural 
and unartificial, so there must be some truth at the bottom of them. 
But what truth? 

So much is clear, that a complex can only be given by means of its 
description; and this description will hold or not hold. [See 3 .24.] 

The proposition dealing with a complex will not be nonsensical 
if the complex does not exist, but simply false. [See 3.24.] 

wr, 16.5. 15. 

When I see space do I see all its points? 

It is no more possible to present something "contradicting logic" 
in language than to present a figure contradicting the laws of space 
in geometry by means of its co-ordinates, or, say, to give the co- 
ordinates of a point that does not exist. [3.032.] 

If there were propositions asserting the existence of proto-pictures 
they would be unique and would be a kind of "logical propositions" 
and the set of these propositions would give logic an impossible 
reality. There would be co-ordination in logic. 

18.5. 15. 
The possibility of all similes, of the whole pictorial character of our 
language, is founded in the logic of portrayal. [4.01 5 .] 



