The thing is that here it is very easy to confuse the logical product 
and the logical sum. 

For we come to the apparently remarkable result that two proposi- 
tions must have something in common in order to be capable of being 
asserted by one proposition. 

(Belonging to a single class, however, is also something that proposi- 
